00:34:43,848 --> 00:34:46,516
Yeah, look at his great-grandmother.

567
00:34:46,516 --> 00:34:48,885
Blind and paralyzed.

568
00:34:49,353 --> 00:34:51,054
Whenever there's a crisis,

569
00:34:51,054 --> 00:34:53,957
the H18 chip automatically rescues her.

570
00:34:53,958 --> 00:34:54,692
We really...

571
00:34:54,692 --> 00:34:57,562
can't live nor die in peace.

572
00:34:57,562 --> 00:34:58,663
Don't say that.

573
00:34:58,663 --> 00:35:00,765
Life is precious.

574
00:35:00,765 --> 00:35:02,800
Is it not? Life is so precious.

575
00:35:02,800 --> 00:35:05,002
Don't you think so?

576
00:35:05,002 --> 00:35:06,871
What's precious about our lives?

577
00:35:06,871 --> 00:35:08,339
We're poor

578
00:35:09,107 --> 00:35:10,041
Have some fruit

579
00:35:10,041 --> 00:35:11,509
Our family

580
00:35:11,509 --> 00:35:13,811
has worked like cattle all our lives.

581
00:35:13,878 --> 00:35:16,981
Not knowing when it will end

582
00:35:17,682 --> 00:35:21,419
That's why Benji did such a foolish thing.

583
00:35:24,455 --> 00:35:25,423
Actually

584
00:35:26,257 --> 00:35:28,259
many charities

585
00:35:28,259 --> 00:35:31,129
offer some relief programs.

586
00:35:31,129 --> 00:35:33,731
For example, us, the Immortality Society

587
00:35:34,899 --> 00:35:38,469
provides emergency aid funds.

588
00:35:39,804 --> 00:35:41,172
The Immortality Society?

589
00:35:42,473 --> 00:35:44,842
You're from the Immortality Society?

590
00:35:44,842 --> 00:35:46,677
Yeah

591
00:35:46,677 --> 00:35:50,548
It's hard enough for us young people to stay alive

592
00:35:50,548 --> 00:35:51,983
Unlike you all,

593
00:35:51,983 --> 00:35:53,784
Even have leftover resources for good deeds

594
00:35:53,784 --> 00:35:56,287
Lily, don't talk like that

595
00:35:56,287 --> 00:35:59,390
Grandpa, we can't accept anything from the Immortality Society.

596
00:36:01,826 --> 00:36:03,628
Great-grandma.

597
00:36:14,038 --> 00:36:14,872
Sorry.

598
00:36:14,872 --> 00:36:17,608
I was late because of a meeting with the Vice President.

599
00:36:17,608 --> 00:36:19,010
No problem.

600
00:36:20,077 --> 00:36:21,245
Sorry to interrupt, sir

601
00:36:21,245 --> 00:36:22,180
The private room is ready.

602
00:36:22,180 --> 00:36:23,314
This way, please.

603
00:36:27,385 --> 00:36:30,121
I visited the home of the bomber.

604
00:36:30,121 --> 00:36:31,589
Benji Lee

605
00:36:33,157 --> 00:36:35,159
Why did you go there?

606
00:36:37,128 --> 00:36:40,031
There must be a reason

607
00:36:40,031 --> 00:36:41,632
why he risked his life to protest.

608
00:36:42,667 --> 00:36:44,035
Sure enough,

609
00:36:45,269 --> 00:36:48,973
his family is sick and poor.

610
00:36:50,741 --> 00:36:54,378
The kid was right.

611
00:36:54,378 --> 00:36:57,181
Their lives seem endless with no way out.

612
00:37:00,251 --> 00:37:01,552
So?

613
00:37:02,353 --> 00:37:03,454
So,

614
00:37:04,622 --> 00:37:07,959
I'm planning to cancel the public application for the H99.

615
00:37:09,527 --> 00:37:11,195
God

616
00:37:12,396 --> 00:37:14,565
How are you so soft-hearted?

617
00:37:16,901 --> 00:37:20,037
If young people work hard, won't they have opportunities?

618
00:37:21,205 --> 00:37:23,874
They're too eager to take resources from the elderly.

619
00:37:25,009 --> 00:37:27,678
Have they thought about what they've contributed?

620
00:37:29,480 --> 00:37:31,148
Everything in this world

621
00:37:31,148 --> 00:37:34,252
was built by our generation, wasn't it?

622
00:37:41,492 --> 00:37:42,426
Here,

623
00:37:42,426 --> 00:37:44,762
Come in and sit with me, let me tell you

624
00:37:46,464 --> 00:37:48,833
Instead of dwelling on these useless things

625
00:37:50,234 --> 00:37:52,103
Why not go do some charity work?

626
00:37:56,674 --> 00:38:01,212
Accumulating more social welfare points is more practical.

627
00:38:06,517 --> 00:38:09,754
It's the end of March now.

628
00:38:09,754 --> 00:38:11,622
Spring is here.

629
00:38:16,360 --> 00:38:18,929
In the yard of this nursing home,

630
00:38:18,929 --> 00:38:22,900
there's a large green lawn.

631
00:38:23,534 --> 00:38:25,169
It's very fresh

632
00:38:27,672 --> 00:38:30,374
Don't you think life is beautiful?

633
00:38:57,001 --> 00:38:58,536
Sir

634
00:38:58,536 --> 00:38:59,870
Should we head back to the office?

635
00:39:02,173 --> 00:39:05,476
Thank you, for driving for me

636
00:39:06,677 --> 00:39:10,348
I can never get used to the auto-pilot thing

637
00:39:10,348 --> 00:39:12,616
I need to thank you, really

638
00:39:12,616 --> 00:39:17,121
For giving me this part-time job and help me settle my mother

639
00:39:17,121 --> 00:39:20,491
But I haven't told my family yet.

640
00:39:20,491 --> 00:39:21,992
I'm afraid it might bother them.

641
00:39:23,694 --> 00:39:24,895
It's ok

642
00:39:25,730 --> 00:39:27,264
Then don'y

643
00:39:41,412 --> 00:39:42,847
Let's talk about your work.

644
00:39:45,783 --> 00:39:47,118
Do you want to talk about lights?

645
00:39:48,285 --> 00:39:52,022
Do you know... if it weren't for light bulb companies

646
00:39:52,022 --> 00:39:54,925
setting lifespan limits on light bulbs

647
00:39:54,925 --> 00:39:58,696
to keep producing them,

648
00:39:59,530 --> 00:40:02,299
those bulbs would never actually break?

649
00:40:06,137 --> 00:40:10,708
Since technology can make light bulbs last forever,

650
00:40:10,708 --> 00:40:15,780
people should be able to live forever too.

651
00:40:23,721 --> 00:40:26,791
But if you're always so grumpy,

652
00:40:26,791 --> 00:40:30,461
what's the point of living forever?

653
00:40:30,461 --> 00:40:32,563
There's no quality of life at all.

654
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:38,803
I need to reflect on that, I will.

655
00:40:40,271 --> 00:40:41,772
If there were some technology

656
00:40:41,772 --> 00:40:47,144
that could fix my short temper, that would be great.

657
00:40:48,746 --> 00:40:53,184
Our company just developed a "Quantum Starlight."

658
00:40:53,551 --> 00:40:56,720
It's said to calm people's emotions.

659
00:40:56,720 --> 00:40:58,789
Would you like to try it?

660
00:41:11,602 --> 00:41:15,039
This doesn't look like a lab at all

661
00:41:16,073 --> 00:41:18,609
Just think of it as a lounge.

662
00:41:19,944 --> 00:41:22,346
Turn on the Quantum Starlight.

663
00:41:28,586 --> 00:41:29,854
This Quantum Starlight

664
00:41:29,854 --> 00:41:32,156
uses quantum tunneling properties.

665
00:41:32,523 --> 00:41:35,960
The information it carries can enter the cerebral cortex.

666
00:41:35,960 --> 00:41:39,663
This information enters the brain through light quanta

667
00:41:39,663 --> 00:41:42,399
and combines with neurotransmitters,

668
00:41:42,399 --> 00:41:46,203
causing the body to release more serotonin and dopamine.

669
00:41:48,639 --> 00:41:51,475
What do those... amines do?

670
00:41:51,742 --> 00:41:53,077
Serotonin and dopamine

671
00:41:53,077 --> 00:41:55,513
It can reduce stress and calm emotions,

672
00:41:55,513 --> 00:41:58,249
making people feel happy and peaceful,

673
00:41:58,249 --> 00:42:00,584
like being embraced by nature.

674
00:42:03,420 --> 00:42:05,122
I get it.

675
00:42:05,122 --> 00:42:08,092
So, this is a type of lightbulb

676
00:42:08,092 --> 00:42:09,894
beneficial for mental and physical health.

677
00:42:11,562 --> 00:42:12,730
Yeah

678
00:42:13,464 --> 00:42:14,865
Sounds nice

679
00:42:17,034 --> 00:42:20,771
Here, relax, lay down

680
00:42:22,439 --> 00:42:23,874
Go on

681
00:42:49,400 --> 00:42:51,135
Take some time and rest up.

682
00:42:52,036 --> 00:42:55,639
I'll go have a few words with the designer

683
00:42:56,073 --> 00:42:58,375
About the parameters that suit you best

684
00:43:18,162 --> 00:43:20,931
Sir, I'm ready

685
00:43:23,500 --> 00:43:24,702
Let's begin

686
00:43:44,622 --> 00:43:47,291
Sir, his brainwaves

687
00:43:47,291 --> 00:43:48,959
have gradually stabilized.

688
00:43:50,260 --> 00:43:53,030
And look, his VTA

689
00:43:53,430 --> 00:43:55,899
is secreting a large amount of dopamine.

690
00:43:55,899 --> 00:43:57,434
He will feel very comfortable.

691
00:44:02,473 --> 00:44:05,376
Let him have a good sleep first.

692
00:44:05,743 --> 00:44:07,845
He has been really tired lately.

693
00:44:15,719 --> 00:44:16,787
Elsie

694
00:44:26,830 --> 00:44:29,133
I want to hold onto you.

695
00:44:31,168 --> 00:44:32,870
I want to be with you.

696
00:45:18,082 --> 00:45:19,550
Why aren't you communicating with me?

697
00:45:32,262 --> 00:45:34,198
You have completely forgotten me

698
00:45:43,340 --> 00:45:45,242
I finally understand

699
00:45:45,242 --> 00:45:47,578
Why humans fear death

700
00:45:51,248 --> 00:45:53,217
Because once they die

701
00:45:53,217 --> 00:45:55,452
They lose all the things they originally have.

702
00:46:04,061 --> 00:46:05,362
I guess this is why

703
00:46:05,362 --> 00:46:06,830
Humans pursue immortality

704
00:46:07,131 --> 00:46:09,099
However, considering how humans treat life,

705
00:46:09,099 --> 00:46:11,769
I feel that a limited lifespan might be better for them.

706
00:46:13,137 --> 00:46:15,973
So humans are supposed to die, aren't they?
